# Project Rules — Spatial-Cognition QA Benchmark for VLMs

You are reviewing and helping write code for a research benchmark. Read
this file fully before answering any request in this repo. When I ask for
a review, first read the actual files, map them against the architecture
and invariants below, then report deviations by severity and propose
concrete diffs. Do not invent modules, fields, or features that aren't
described here; if something is missing or ambiguous, say so and ask
before making large changes.

## Fill in before first use
- Language / runtime: Python 3.12
- Key libs: pydantic (schema + invariant enforcement), pyyaml (construct
  configs), pytest (invariant tests), Pillow (multi-image frames),
  litellm or provider SDK (agent + VLM calls), pandas + seaborn
  (reporting), sqlite/sqlalchemy/json (Item Store)
- Dev tools (not runtime deps): Cursor (editor)
- Data source(s): AI2-THOR (collected), Matterport3D (planned)

## What this project is
A question-answering benchmark that probes spatial cognition in
vision-language models (VLMs). Items are multi-image (frame sequences
from 3D simulators) + a multiple-choice question. The benchmark must
measure genuine visual-spatial reasoning, NOT language priors.

## Taxonomy (the capability axis)
Four classes, eight constructs, treated as a **partially-ordered
pipeline** (later stages subsume earlier ones — not fully independent):
1. Spatial encoding — egocentric; allocentric (object-to-object)
2. Spatial memory — spatial working memory; invisible displacement
3. Operation on the cognitive map — spatial updating; perspective-taking
4. Navigation / wayfinding — route knowledge; survey knowledge
Cross-cutting axis on every item: `frame_of_reference` ∈ {egocentric, allocentric}.
Headline analyses are per-construct and per-(construct × frame_of_reference).

## Architecture (respect this structure)
Two pipelines under one Orchestrator, separated by an immutable FREEZE.
Tag each node [AGENT] = LLM call, [CODE] = deterministic, no model.

- Benchmark Orchestrator [CODE] — owns run order, versioning
  - Config Registry — 8 construct configs (static YAML, single source of truth)
  - Item Store / DB — shared state; what gets frozen
  - Item Generation Pipeline
    - Task Planner [AGENT] — pick scene + construct + FoR, apply episode filter
    - Question Generator [AGENT] — write question + answer FROM metadata
    - Distractor Generator [AGENT] — plausible, diagnostic options
    - Ground-truth Validator [CODE] — recompute answer from CSV; must match
    - Vision-necessity Verifier [CODE + model calls] — blind-LLM & caption baselines
    - Judge / Filter [AGENT + CODE] — well-formed, FoR stated, dedup
    - Set Balancer [CODE] — equalize counts per construct × ego/allo
  - === FREEZE / version tag === (the wall; frozen set is immutable)
  - Model Evaluation Pipeline (consumes frozen set ONLY)
    - Model Runner [CODE] — fixed protocol, identical for every VLM
    - Response Parser [CODE; AGENT only to map prose→option label]
    - Deterministic Scorer [CODE] — exact-match; per-construct/FoR breakdown
    - Error Analysis Agent [AGENT] — failure modes from structured logs
    - Evaluation Reporter [CODE] — tables, baselines, gaps

## Invariants — never violate; flag any code that does
1. Generators never invent spatial facts. Every question/answer is
   composed from CSV metadata only.
2. Every item has a non-null `answer_source` pointing at the metadata
   field(s) the answer derives from. No answer without traceability.
3. Ground-truth Validator, Model Runner, and Deterministic Scorer are
   pure [CODE]. An LLM must never judge answer correctness — results
   must be reproducible.
4. `vision_necessary == true` is required for an item to enter the
   frozen set (both blind-LLM and caption→LLM baselines must FAIL it).
5. The FREEZE wall is one-directional: nothing observed during
   evaluation may edit, filter, or regenerate items. No tuning to models.
6. Generator and Validator use different models/prompts, so the checker
   isn't just agreeing with the writer.
7. Distractors are spatially plausible AND diagnostic (each wrong option
   maps to a specific failure mode, e.g. the pre-move bearing = the
   non-updating error). All options must be real locations/directions
   present in the scene.
8. Construct isolation lives in each config's `must_hold` block — treat
   those as hard rejects, enforced in code, not suggestions.

## Item schema (fields on a finished item)
Core: item_id, construct, class, frame_of_reference, environment,
scene_id, image_paths[], question, options{}, answer, answer_source.
Recommended: agent_trajectory (pose per frame), agent_actions (ordered),
queried_object_id, distractor_rationale{}, difficulty.
Temporal (required only for object-moves / observer-moves constructs):
object_state_track[], displacement_event{}.
Verification (set by pipeline, NOT the generator; start null):
blind_llm_correct, caption_llm_correct, vision_necessary.

## Episode GT notes (pre-item ledger)
- Built from SPOC collection folder via `--csv_path_folder` (see README).
- System of record: SQLite EpisodeStore; JSON export is optional.
- Sparse fields: object_state_track (displaced objects only),
  region_trajectory, passage_state — carry-forward at query step t.
- distance_label (how far) ≠ angle_relation front/behind (local +Z).
  "beyond" + "front" means ahead of the agent but far.
- Do not invent object facing from obj-rot unless a trusted source exists.
- Collector field brief: prompts/ai2thor_collection_extension.md.

## How to review / suggest
- Start by mapping files → architecture nodes; name any node with no
  code, or code that belongs to no node.
- Check each invariant explicitly and cite the file/line that breaks it.
- Prioritize: (1) invariant violations, (2) reproducibility risks in the
  eval pipeline, (3) separation-of-concerns leaks between the two
  pipelines, (4) correctness, (5) style.
- Prefer small, reviewable diffs. Explain the "why" in one line each.
- Reuse, don't duplicate: the Vision-necessity Verifier and Model Runner
  share baseline-calling machinery — build it once and call from both.
- Suggest tests that assert the invariants (e.g. a test that fails if any
  frozen item has null answer_source or vision_necessary != true).
- If a request would blur the FREEZE wall or make an [CODE] node call an
  LLM for scoring, refuse and explain.
